all Street Journal </i>reported that succession planning at The Est=C3=A9e =
Lauder Companies had indeed commenced. The family-owned beauty giant is loo=
king both externally and internally=E2=80=94and likely within the family, i=
tself=E2=80=94as it conducts an executive search to <i>eventually</i> repla=
ce C.E.O. <b>Fabrizio Freda</b>, who ostensibly retains the full support of=
 the board, the <b>Lauder </b>clan, etcetera. Despite the company=E2=80=99s=
 market value plunging from $133 billion to barely $43 billion in three yea=
rs, the <i>Journal</i> piece once again confirmed the Lauder party line: Th=
e executive who=E2=80=99s spent 15 years at the helm is not yet abandoning =
his perch atop the GM Building, which has served as the company=E2=80=99s h=
eadquarters for 55 years.<br/> <br/>As is the case with any centibillion-do=
llar, family-controlled empire, the dynamics behind
the scenes are nuanced. Freda has long enjoyed the support of <b>William</b=
> <b>Lauder</b>, the 64-year-old heir, who also served as his predecessor b=
efore ascending to executive chairman and chairman of the board of director=
s in 2009. William=E2=80=99s five-year reign saw a reduction of ELC=E2=80=
=99s dependence on department stores, and the debut of Origins and Tom Ford=
 Beauty (which was largely engineered by <b>John Demsey</b>), but was never=
theless far less exalted than the legendary tenure of his impossibly elegan=
t father, <b>Leonard Lauder</b>. From 1982 to 1999, after all, Leonard expa=
nded upon his parents=E2=80=99 namesake through shrewd and dynastic M&amp;A=
=2E Within a span of just a few years,=20=
the company acquired MAC Cosmetics, La=
 Mer, Jo Malone London, and Bobbi Brown=E2=80=94some of the most lucrative =
brands in the portfolio to this day. <br/></td>
