          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Indeed, Freda has e=
ffectively, if belatedly, pushed for modernization. He has since reversed h=
imself and committed his brands to partnerships with Amazon, once an unspea=
kable notion at Est=C3=A9e Lauder. (As of this week, Too Faced now has an o=
fficial presence on Amazon, following on the heels of Clinique.) The longti=
me reluctance is reminiscent of the company=E2=80=99s labored decision to b=
elatedly enter Sephora and Ulta. =E2=80=9CThey have to turn around and now =
allow their brands to go on Amazon,=E2=80=9D this person added. =E2=80=9CTh=
ey=E2=80=99re doing it from a place of desperation.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>In th=
e meantime, Freda remains intent on =E2=80=9Cowning the night,=E2=80=9D his=
 attempt to compete against L=E2=80=99Or=C3=A9al, which he believes =E2=80=
=9Cowns the day,=E2=80=9D according to the current Lauder executive. Others=
 have described a fixation with nighttime products=E2=80=93=E2=80=93which i=
nclude skincare, makeup, and
fragrance=E2=80=94as a =E2=80=9Cone-size-fits-all=E2=80=9D approach that fa=
ils to take brand, price, and category expertise into consideration. Freda =
is still trying to re-create the success of flagship brand Est=C3=A9e Laude=
r=E2=80=99s 42-year-old hero product, Advanced Night Repair, even when it d=
oesn=E2=80=99t necessarily make sense. Some notable recent examples include=
 makeup line Bobbi Brown=E2=80=99s pricey serum that =E2=80=9Cnourishes ove=
rnight,=E2=80=9D and Jo Malone London=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cnight collection=
=E2=80=9D of fragrances. =E2=80=9CYou can charge higher price points,=E2=80=
=9D this person said of night-specific products like serums and richer crea=
ms. =E2=80=9CJust because people will spend more at night, Fabrizio believe=
s that there=E2=80=99s more of an opportunity to win there.=E2=80=9D Freda =
encouraged cosmetics brands to create products marketed specifically for th=
e evening, too. <br/><br/>Additionally, Freda pushed makeup brands to devel=
op skincare=E2=80=93=E2=80=93even if they had no authority to do so=E2=80=
=93=E2=80=93because it was inexpensive to make, and they could
charge more money than they could for a lipstick or foundation. It was also=
 another way to reach the skincare-obsessed Chinese consumer that the compa=
ny relied on during the boom years. When MAC launched skincare in January o=
f last year, I heard that Freda pulled Clinique=E2=80=99s longtime product =
development lead, <b>Janet</b> <b>Pardo</b>, to work on the inaugural lineu=
p. =E2=80=9CMAC doing skincare was a Fabrizio top-down directive,=E2=80=9D =
another current executive said. =E2=80=9CWe were all sitting there saying, =
<i>No one is going to buy this</i>.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>It=E2=80=99s hard to =
tell a simple story about which of Freda=E2=80=99s initiatives has and hasn=
=E2=80=99t worked. His focus on artisanal, or higher-end, perfume seems to =
be paying off: Lauder=E2=80=99s fragrance business has grown in 11 of the p=
ast 12 quarters, I=E2=80=99m told, driven by Le Labo (a 2014 acquisition), =
Jo Malone, and Tom Ford. At the same time, while the Est=C3=A9e Lauder Comp=
anies stock is down almost 70 percent from an all-time high in 2021, it has
also almost doubled in 10 years while paying a hefty dividend. The collapse=
 of the share price from its pandemic-era high must surely bother the famil=
y, which owns 38 percent of the common stock (and 86 percent of the voting =
stock). But a family concern like Lauder is also accustomed to thinking in =
decades, not years. And Freda won=E2=80=99t be replaced until they say so=
=E2=80=94whether his successor is in the family or not. <br/></td>
         </tr>
